oundbreaking and intriguing study of Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm’s Nursery and Household Tales. This expanded edition includes a new preface and an appendix featuring translations of six tales with commentary by Maria Tatar. Throughout the book, Tatar draws on the disciplinary tools of psychoanalysis and folklore while also providing historical context to explore the harsher aspects of these stories, presenting new interpretations of tales that engage in a kind of cultural repetition compulsion. No other book so thoroughly challenges us to rethink the happily-ever-after of these classic stories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFairy taleszGermanyvHistory and criticism. 0aFairy taleszGermanyxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Fairy Tales, Folk Tales, Legends & Mythology.2bisacsh  aAllusion.  aAnecdote.  aAngela Carter.  aBleak House.  aBluebeard.  aBobbin.  aBriar Rose (novel).  aBrothers Grimm.  aBruno Bettelheim.  aCannibalism.  aCautionary tale.  aCharles Dickens.  aCharles Perrault.  aChild abandonment.  aChild abuse.  aChildren's literature.  aCinderella.  aCoffin.  aCriticism.  aCrone.  aCruelty.  aDecapitation.  aDisenchantment.  aDorothea Viehmann.  aElectra complex.  aEvil Queen (Disney).  aFable.  aFairy tale.  aFiction.  aFledgling (novel).  aFolk and Fairy Tales.  aFolklore.  aGiambattista Basile.  aGolden Hair (fairy tale).  aGrimms' Fairy Tales.  aHans My Hedgehog.  aHansel and Gretel.  aHousehold.  aHumiliation.  aIllustration.  aIn the Woods.  aIncest.  aInfanticide.  aItalian Folktales.  aItalo Calvino.  aJack Zipes.  aJacob Grimm.  aKing Thrushbeard.  aLiterary criticism.  aLiterature.  aLittle Red Riding Hood.  aLudwig Bechstein.  aMary's Child.  aMelodrama.  aMisfortune (folk t